 <h2 style="color:orange">Electricity 
  </h2>
  <img src="https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2016/11/23/17/59/light-1854093_1280.jpg", width="30%">
  </img><br>
<b>Electricity</b><sup> [<b>Note</b>:Electricity is a form of energy that produces heat, light and power.]
</sup>
is produced in power plants and carried to your home via the electric power grid.
<hr>
<h2 style="color:green;">Nonrewable Energy Resources</h2>
<img src="https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2014/06/21/20/11/power-station-374097_1280.jpg", width="30%">
  </img><br>
<p>Nonrenewable energy sources are those that exist in a limited supply and cannot be replaced or replenished as quickly as they are used. There are two main types of nonrenewable energy sources:</p>
<ul>
 <li>1. Fossil Fuels: Fossil fuels <sub><i>(coal, petroleum/crude oil, and natural gas)</sub></i> formed from the buried remains of plants and animals that lived millions of years ago.</li>
   <li>2. Nuclear Energy: Nuclear power is energy in the nucleus (core) of an atom. Splitting atoms produces heat, which makes electricity, in a nuclear power plant.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 style="color:Purple">Renewable Energy Resources 
  </h2>
<img src="https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2022/01/10/15/29/wind-mills-6928590_1280.jpg", width="50%"></img><br>
The most common renewable energy sources are
<ol>
  <li><b><i>Hydroelectric power</b></i>, or <span style="color:red;"> hydropower</span>, uses flowing water to turn turbines to produce electricity.</li>
  <li><b><i>Solar energy</b></i> uses a variety of technologies to convert sunlight to usable energy. <span style="color:red;">Energy from the sun can be used to heat water, heat or cool air, and generate electricity for individual homes or buildings.</span> On a large scale, it can be used to produce electricity to power cities and small towns.</li>
  <li><b><i>Wind energy</b></i> <span style="color:red;">uses air blowing across propeller blades</span> causing them to spin to produce electricity.</li>
</ol>
